{"award_age":33.0,"bio_image":"full\/ce5b9c7259f4b7b1fad77b046df4fe491894aa3e.jpg","category":"Peace","country":"Ireland","date_of_birth":"1943-05-22T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"female","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/b\/b7\/Betty_Williams.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Betty_Williams_(Nobel_laureate)","mini_bio":"<p><b>Betty Williams<\/b> (born 22 May 1943) in the city of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Belfast\" title=\"Belfast\">Belfast<\/a> in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Northern_Ireland\" title=\"Northern Ireland\">Northern Ireland<\/a>, is a co-recipient with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mairead_Corrigan\" title=\"Mairead Corrigan\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Mairead Corrigan<\/a> of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Peace_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Peace Prize\">Nobel Peace Prize<\/a> in 1976 for her work as a cofounder of <b>Community of Peace People<\/b>, an organisation dedicated to promoting a peaceful resolution to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Troubles\" title=\"The Troubles\">the Troubles<\/a> in Northern Ireland.<\/p><p>Williams heads the Global Children's Foundation and is the President of the World Centre of Compassion for Children International. She is also the Chair of Institute for Asian Democracy in Washington D.C. and a Distinguished Visiting Professor at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nova_Southeastern_University\" title=\"Nova Southeastern University\">Nova Southeastern University<\/a>. She lectures widely on topics of peace, education, inter-cultural and inter-faith understanding, anti-extremism, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Children%27s_rights\" title=\"Children's rights\">children's rights<\/a>.<\/p><p>Williams is a founding member of the Nobel Laureate Summit, which has taken place annually since 2000.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Betty_Williams_(Nobel_laureate)#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>In 2006, Williams became a founder of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Women%27s_Initiative\" title=\"Nobel Women's Initiative\">Nobel Women's Initiative<\/a> along with Nobel Peace Laureates <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mairead_Corrigan_Maguire\" title=\"Mairead Corrigan Maguire\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Mairead Corrigan Maguire<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Shirin_Ebadi\" title=\"Shirin Ebadi\">Shirin Ebadi<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Wangari_Maathai\" title=\"Wangari Maathai\">Wangari Maathai<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Jody_Williams\" title=\"Jody Williams\">Jody Williams<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rigoberta_Menchu_Tum\" title=\"Rigoberta Menchu Tum\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Rigoberta Menchu Tum<\/a>. These six women representing North and South America, the Middle East, Europe and Africa, bring together their experiences in a united effort for peace with justice and equality. It is the goal of the Nobel Women's Initiative to help strengthen work being done in support of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Women%27s_rights\" title=\"Women's rights\">women's rights<\/a> around the world. Williams also is a member of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/PeaceJam\" title=\"PeaceJam\">PeaceJam<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Betty Williams","place_of_birth":"Belfast, Northern Ireland","place_of_death":null,"text":"Betty Williams , Peace, 1976","year":1976.0}